# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cataract-beam-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] In physics and mathematics, the **phase** (symbol φ or ϕ) of a wave or other periodic function F of some real variable t (such as time) is an angle-like quantity representing the fraction of the cycle covered up to t .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] It is expressed in such a scale that it varies by one full turn as the variable t goes through each period (and $F(t)$ goes through each complete cycle).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] It may be measured in any angular unit such as degrees or radians, thus increasing by 360° or $2\pi$ as the variable t completes a full period.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] This convention is especially appropriate for a sinusoidal function, since its value at any argument t then can be expressed as $\varphi (t)$ , the sine of the phase, multiplied by some factor (the amplitude of the sinusoid).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Usually, whole turns are ignored when expressing the phase; so that $\varphi (t)$ is also a periodic function, with the same period as F , that repeatedly scans the same range of angles as t goes through each period.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Then, F is said to be "at the same phase" at two argument values $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ (that is, $\varphi (t_{1})=\varphi (t_{2})$ ) if the difference between them is a whole number of periods.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The numeric value of the phase $\varphi (t)$ depends on the arbitrary choice of the start of each period, and on the interval of angles that each period is to be mapped to.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The term "phase" is also used when comparing a periodic function F with a shifted version G of it.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] If the shift in t is expressed as a fraction of the period, and then scaled to an angle $\varphi$ spanning a whole turn, one gets the *phase shift*, *phase offset*, or *phase difference* of G relative to F .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] If F is a "canonical" function for a class of signals, like $\sin(t)$ is for all sinusoidal signals, then $\varphi$ is called the *initial phase* of G .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Let the signal F be a periodic function of one real variable, and T be its period (that is, the smallest positive real number such that $F(t+T)=F(t)$ for all t ).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Here $[\![\,\cdot \,]\!]\!\,$ denotes the fractional part of a real number, discarding its integer part; that is, $[\![x]\!]=x-\left\lfloor x\right\rfloor \!\,$ ; and $t_{0}$ is an arbitrary "origin" value of the argument, that one considers to be the beginning of a cycle.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] This concept can be visualized by imagining a clock with a hand that turns at constant speed, making a full turn every T seconds, and is pointing straight up at time $t_{0}$ .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The phase $\varphi (t)$ is then the angle from the 12:00 position to the current position of the hand, at time t , measured clockwise.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The phase concept is most useful when the origin $t_{0}$ is chosen based on features of F .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] For example, for a sinusoid, a convenient choice is any t where the function's value changes from zero to positive.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The formula above gives the phase as an angle in radians between 0 and $2\pi$ .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The phase expressed in degrees (from 0° to 360°, or from −180° to +180°) is defined the same way, except with "360°" in place of "2π".
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Moreover, for any given choice of the origin $t_{0}$ , the value of the signal F for any argument t depends only on its phase at t .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Namely, one can write $F(t)=f(\varphi (t))$ , where f is a function of an angle, defined only for a single full turn, that describes the variation of F as t ranges over a single period.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] In fact, every periodic signal F with a specific waveform can be expressed as $F(t)=A\,w(\varphi (t))$ where w is a "canonical" function of a phase angle in 0 to 2π, that describes just one cycle of that waveform; and A is a scaling factor for the amplitude.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Since phases are angles, any whole full turns should usually be ignored when performing arithmetic operations on them.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Thus, for example, the sum of phase angles 190° + 200° is 30° (190 + 200 = 390, minus one full turn), and subtracting 50° from 30° gives a phase of 340° (30 − 50 = −20, plus one full turn).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Similar formulas hold for radians, with $2\pi$ instead of 360.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The difference $\varphi (t)=\varphi _{G}(t)-\varphi _{F}(t)$ between the phases of two periodic signals F and G is called the *phase difference* or *phase shift* of G relative to F .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] At values of t when the difference is zero, the two signals are said to be *in phase;* otherwise, they are *out of phase* with each other.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] In the clock analogy, each signal is represented by a hand (or pointer) of the same clock, both turning at constant but possibly different speeds.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The phase difference is then the angle between the two hands, measured clockwise.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The phase difference is particularly important when two signals are added together by a physical process, such as two periodic sound waves emitted by two sources and recorded together by a microphone.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] This is usually the case in linear systems, when the superposition principle holds.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] For arguments t when the phase difference is zero, the two signals will have the same sign and will be reinforcing each other.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] One says that constructive interference is occurring.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] At arguments t when the phases are different, the value of the sum depends on the waveform.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] For sinusoidal signals, when the phase difference $\varphi (t)$ is 180° ( $\pi$ radians), one says that the phases are *opposite*, and that the signals are *in antiphase*.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Then the signals have opposite signs, and destructive interference occurs.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Conversely, a *phase reversal* or *phase inversion* implies a 180-degree phase shift.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] When the phase difference $\varphi (t)$ is a quarter of turn (a right angle, +90° = π/2 or −90° = 270° = −π/2 = 3π/2), sinusoidal signals are sometimes said to be in *quadrature*, e.g., in-phase and quadrature components of a composite signal or even different signals (e.g., voltage and current).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] If the frequencies are different, the phase difference $\varphi (t)$ increases linearly with the argument t .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The periodic changes from reinforcement and opposition cause a phenomenon called beating.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The phase difference is especially important when comparing a periodic signal F with a shifted and possibly scaled version G of it.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] That is, suppose that $G(t)=\alpha \,F(t+\tau )$ for some constants $\alpha ,\tau$ and all t .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Suppose also that the origin for computing the phase of G has been shifted too.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] In that case, the phase difference $\varphi$ is a constant (independent of t ), called the 'phase shift' or 'phase offset' of G relative to F .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] In the clock analogy, this situation corresponds to the two hands turning at the same speed, so that the angle between them is constant.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] If F is a "canonical" representative for a class of signals, like $\sin(t)$ is for all sinusoidal signals, then the phase shift $\varphi$ called simply the *initial phase* of G .
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Therefore, when two periodic signals have the same frequency, they are always in phase, or always out of phase.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Physically, this situation commonly occurs, for many reasons.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] For example, the two signals may be a periodic soundwave recorded by two microphones at separate locations.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Or, conversely, they may be periodic soundwaves created by two separate speakers from the same electrical signal, and recorded by a single microphone.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] They may be a radio signal that reaches the receiving antenna in a straight line, and a copy of it that was reflected off a large building nearby.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] A well-known example of phase difference is the length of shadows seen at different points of Earth.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] For sinusoidal signals (and a few other waveforms, like square or symmetric triangular), a phase shift of 180° is equivalent to a phase shift of 0° with negation of the amplitude.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] When two signals with these waveforms, same period, and opposite phases are added together, the sum $F+G$ is either identically zero, or is a sinusoidal signal with the same period and phase, whose amplitude is the difference of the original amplitudes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The phase shift of the co-sine function relative to the sine function is +90°.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] A real-world example of a sonic phase difference occurs in the warble of a Native American flute.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The amplitude of different harmonic components of same long-held note on the flute come into dominance at different points in the phase cycle.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The phase difference between the different harmonics can be observed on a spectrogram of the sound of a warbling flute.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] A phase comparison can be made by connecting two signals to a two-channel oscilloscope.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The oscilloscope will display two sine signals, as shown in the graphic to the right.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] In the adjacent image, the top sine signal is the test frequency, and the bottom sine signal represents a signal from the reference.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] If the two frequencies were exactly the same, their phase relationship would not change and both would appear to be stationary on the oscilloscope display.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Since the two frequencies are not exactly the same, the reference appears to be stationary and the test signal moves.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] By measuring the rate of motion of the test signal, the offset between frequencies can be determined.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Vertical lines have been drawn through the points where each sine signal passes through zero.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] The bottom of the figure shows bars whose width represents the phase difference between the signals.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] In this case the phase difference is increasing, indicating that the test signal is lower in frequency than the reference.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] These signals are periodic with period ${\textstyle T={\frac {1}{f}}}$ , and they are identical except for a displacement of ${\textstyle {\frac {T}{4}}}$ along the ${\textstyle t}$ axis.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] Absolute phase is the phase of a waveform relative to some standard (strictly speaking, phase is always relative).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/antiphase] To the extent that this standard is accepted by all parties, one can speak of an absolute phase in a particular field of application.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The **atmospheric engine** was invented by Thomas Newcomen in 1712, and is sometimes referred to as the **Newcomen fire engine** (see below) or **Newcomen engine**.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The engine was operated by condensing steam being drawn into the cylinder, thereby creating a partial vacuum which allowed atmospheric pressure to push the piston into the cylinder.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] It is significant as the first practical device to harness steam to produce mechanical work.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Newcomen engines were used throughout Britain and Europe, principally to pump water out of mines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Hundreds were constructed during the 18th century.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] James Watt's later engine design was an improved version of the Newcomen engine that roughly doubled fuel efficiency.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Many atmospheric engines were converted to the Watt design.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] As a result, Watt is today better known than Newcomen in relation to the origin of the steam engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Prior to Newcomen, a number of small steam devices of various sorts had been made, but most were essentially novelties.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Around 1600, a number of experimenters used steam to power small fountains working like a coffee percolator.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] First, a container was filled with water via a pipe, which extended through the top of the container to nearly the bottom.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The bottom of the pipe would be submerged in the water, making the container airtight.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The container was then heated to make the water boil.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The steam generated pressurized the container, but the inner pipe, immersed at the bottom by liquid, and lacking an airtight seal at top, remained at a lower pressure; expanding steam forced the water at the bottom of the container into and up the pipe to spurt out of a nozzle on top.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] These devices had limited effectiveness but illustrated the principle's viability.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In 1606, the Spaniard, Jerónimo de Ayanz y Beaumont, demonstrated and was granted a patent for a steam-powered water pump.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The pump was successfully used to drain the inundated mines of Guadalcanal, Spain.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In 1662, Edward Somerset, 2nd Marquess of Worcester, published a book containing several ideas he had been working on.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] One was for a steam-powered pump to supply water to fountains; the device alternately used a partial vacuum and steam pressure.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Two containers were alternately filled with steam, then sprayed with cold water making the steam within condense; this produced a partial vacuum that would draw water through a pipe up from a well to the container.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] A fresh charge of steam under pressure then drove the water from the container up another pipe to a higher-level header before that steam condensed and the cycle repeated.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] By working the two containers alternately, the delivery rate to the header tank could be increased.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In 1698, Thomas Savery patented a steam-powered pump he called the "Miner's Friend", combining both the expansive power of steam and the vacuum formed through condensation.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The process of cooling and creating the vacuum was fairly slow, so Savery later added an external cold water spray to quickly cool the steam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Savery's invention cannot be strictly regarded as the first steam "engine" since it had no moving parts and could not transmit its power to any external device.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] There were evidently high hopes for the Miner's Friend, which led Parliament to extend the life of the patent by 21 years, so that the 1699 patent would not expire until 1733.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Unfortunately, Savery's device proved much less successful than had been hoped.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] A theoretical problem with Savery's device stemmed from the fact that a vacuum could only raise water to a maximum height of about 30 ft (9 m); to this could be added another 40 ft (12 m), or so, raised by steam pressure.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This was insufficient to pump water out of a mine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In Savery's pamphlet, he suggests setting the boiler and containers on a ledge in the mineshaft and even a series of two or more pumps for deeper levels.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Obviously, these were inconvenient solutions and some sort of mechanical pump working at surface level – one that lifted the water directly instead of "sucking" it up – was desirable.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Such pumps were common already, powered by horses, but required a vertical reciprocating drive that Savery's system did not provide.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The more practical problem concerned having a boiler operating under pressure, as demonstrated when the boiler of an engine at Wednesbury exploded, perhaps in 1705.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Engines based on the Savery design, albeit enhanced over time, were installed and used as returning engines, raising water to boost the supply to existing water wheels, examples are known in Manchester and Lancashire.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Louis Figuier in his monumental work gives a full quotation of Denis Papin's paper published in 1690 in *Acta eruditorum* at Leipzig, entitled *"Nouvelle méthode pour obtenir à bas prix des forces considérables"* (A new method for cheaply obtaining considerable forces).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] It seems that the idea came to Papin while working with Robert Boyle at the Royal Society in London.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The piston was then temporarily locked in the upper position by a spring catch engaging a notch in the rod.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The fire was then removed, allowing the cylinder to cool, which condensed steam back into water, thus creating a vacuum beneath the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] To the end of the piston rod was attached a cord passing over two pulleys and a weight hung down from the cord's end.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Upon releasing the catch, the piston was sharply drawn down to the bottom of the cylinder by the pressure differential between the atmosphere and the created vacuum; enough force was thus generated to raise a 60 lb (27 kg) weight.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Newcomen took forward Papin's experiment and made it workable, although little information exists as to exactly how this came about.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The way forward was to provide, as Savery had, a boiler capable of ensuring the continuity of the supply of steam to the cylinder, providing the vacuum power stroke by condensing the steam, and disposing of the water once it had been condensed.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The power piston was hung by chains from the end of a rocking beam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Unlike Savery's device, pumping was entirely mechanical, the work of the steam engine being to lift a weighted rod slung from the opposite extremity of the rocking beam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The rod descended the mine shaft by gravity and drove a force pump, or pole pump (or most often a gang of two) inside the mineshaft.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The suction stroke of the pump was only for the length of the upward (priming) stroke, there consequently was no longer the 30-foot restriction of a vacuum pump and water could be forced up a column from far greater depths.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The boiler supplied the steam at extremely low pressure and was at first located immediately beneath the power cylinder but could also be placed behind a separating wall with a connecting steam pipe.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The earliest examples for which reliable records exist were two engines in the Black Country, of which the more famous was that erected in 1712 at the Conygree Coalworks in Bloomfield Road Tipton now the site of "The Angle Ring Company Limited", Tipton.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This is generally accepted as the first successful Newcomen engine and followed by one built a mile and a half east of Wolverhampton.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Both these were used by Newcomen and his partner John Calley to pump out water-filled coal mines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] A working replica can today be seen at the nearby Black Country Living Museum, which stands on another part of what was Lord Dudley's Conygree Park.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Another Newcomen engine was in Cornwall.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Its location is uncertain, but it is known that one was in operation at Wheal Vor mine in 1715.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Soon orders from wet mines all over England were coming in, and some have suggested that word of his achievement was spread through his Baptist connections.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Since Savery's patent had not yet run out, Newcomen was forced to come to an arrangement with Savery and operate under the latter's patent, as its term was much longer than any Newcomen could have easily obtained.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] During the latter years of its currency, the patent belonged to an unincorporated company, *The Proprietors of the Invention for raising water by fire*.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Although its first use was in coal-mining areas, Newcomen's engine was also used for pumping water out of the metal mines in his native West Country, such as the tin mines of Cornwall.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] By the time of his death, Newcomen and others had installed over a hundred of his engines, not only in the West Country and the Midlands but also in north Wales, near Newcastle and in Cumbria.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Small numbers were built in other European countries, including in France, Belgium, Spain, and Hungary, also at Dannemora, Sweden.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Evidence of the use of a Newcomen Steam Engine associated with early coal mines was found in 2010 in Midlothian, VA (site of some of the first coal mines in the US).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] (Dutton and Associates survey dated 24 November 2009).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Although based on simple principles, Newcomen's engine was rather complex and showed signs of incremental development, problems being empirically addressed as they arose.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] It consisted of a boiler **A**, usually a haystack boiler, situated directly below the cylinder.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This produced large quantities of very low pressure steam, no more than 1–2 psi (0.07–0.14 bar) – the maximum allowable pressure for a boiler that in earlier versions was made of copper with a domed top of lead and later entirely assembled from small riveted iron plates.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The action of the engine was transmitted through a rocking "Great balanced Beam", the fulcrum **E** of which rested on the very solid end-gable wall of the purpose-built engine house with the pump side projecting outside of the building, the engine being located *in-house*.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The pump rods were slung by a chain from the arch-head **F** of the great beam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] From the in-house arch-head **D** was suspended a piston **P** working in a cylinder **B**, the top end of which was open to the atmosphere above the piston and the bottom end closed, apart from the short admission pipe connecting the cylinder to the boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Early cylinders were made of cast brass, but cast iron was soon found more effective and much cheaper to produce.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The first to use cast iron was reported to be the engine installed at Hawarden in Wales between 1714 and 1715.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Among the foundries producing and boring iron Newcomen engine cylinders were Coalbrookdale and later the Carron ironworks.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The piston was initially surrounded by a seal in the form of a leather ring, but as the cylinder bore was finished by hand and not absolutely true, a layer of water had to be constantly maintained on top of the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Later soft hemp rope packing was used with iron weights above to keep it in place.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The piston was insulated from the steam, which it would otherwise condense, by bolting wood to the underside.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Installed high up in the engine house was a water tank **C** (or *header tank*) fed by a small in-house pump slung from a smaller arch-head.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The pump equipment was heavier than the steam piston, so that the position of the beam at rest was pump-side down/engine-side up, which was called "out of the house".
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] To start the engine, the regulator valve **V** was opened and steam admitted into the cylinder from the boiler, filling the space beneath the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The regulator valve was then closed and the water injection valve **V'** briefly snapped open and shut, sending a spray of cold water into the cylinder.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This condensed the steam and created a partial vacuum under the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Pressure differential between the atmosphere above the piston and the partial vacuum below then drove the piston down making the power stroke, bringing the beam "into the house", raising the pump gear and pumping the water up from the mine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Steam was then readmitted to the cylinder, destroying the vacuum and driving the condensate down the sinking or "eduction" pipe.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] As the low pressure steam from the boiler flowed into the cylinder, the weight of the pump and gear returned the beam to its initial position.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This cycle was repeated around 12 times per minute.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Newcomen found that his first engine would stop working after a while, and eventually discovered that this was due to small amounts of air being admitted to the cylinder with the steam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Water usually contains some dissolved air, and boiling the water released this with the steam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This air could not be condensed by the water spray and gradually accumulated until the engine became "wind logged".
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] To prevent this, a release valve called a "snifting clack" or snifter valve was included near the bottom of the cylinder.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This opened briefly when steam was first introduced, and non-condensable gas was driven from the cylinder.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Its name was derived from the noise it made when it operated to release the air and steam "like a Man snifting with a Cold".
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In early versions, the valves or *plugs* as they were then called, were operated manually by the *plug man* but the repetitive action demanded precise timing, making automatic action desirable.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] On the 1712 engine, the water feed pump was attached to the bottom of the plug tree, but later engines had the pump outside suspended from a separate small arch-head.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Because of the very heavy steam demands, the engine had to be periodically stopped and restarted, but even this process was automated by means of a buoy rising and falling in a vertical stand pipe fixed to the boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The buoy was attached to the *scoggen*, a weighted lever that worked a stop blocking the water injection valve shut until more steam had been raised.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The design of pumps used for coal mines with Newcomen engines are discussed in some detail in John Farey's book "A treatise on the steam engine", published in 1827.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Water is rarely raised to the surface, but instead is pumped from the base of the shaft to an adit level which is a slowly descending shaft driven to a suitable low point to discharge the water.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] At the base of the shaft the pump draws water into the base section by suction (the pump is called a sucking pump as a result), and thence above a non-return valve into the main pump body.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The pump piston incorporates a valve which opens on the downstroke and then closes lifting the column of water above into a column made of iron pipes joined with lead gaskets.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The normal maximum lift is 50 yards due to the water pressure in the iron pipes, which have to be strong enough to withstand the pressure and a degree of shock.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The pump rod may be divided to operate multiple pumps to overcome this limitation, each one lifting water into a cistern which feeds into the pump above.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] One particular consideration is to make sure the pumps do not draw in air as the resulting shocks can damage the pump system and the engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Towards the close of its career, the atmospheric engine was much improved in its mechanical details and its proportions by John Smeaton, who built many large engines of this type during the 1770s.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The urgent need for an engine to give rotary motion was making itself felt and this was done with limited success by Wasborough and Pickard using a Newcomen engine to drive a flywheel through a crank.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] By 1725 the Newcomen engine was in common use in mining, particularly collieries.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] It held its place with little material change for the rest of the century.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Use of the Newcomen engine was extended in some places to pump municipal water supply; for instance the first Newcomen engine in France was built at Passy in 1726 to pump water from the Seine to the city of Paris.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] It was also used to power machinery indirectly, by returning water from below a water wheel to a reservoir above it, so that the same water could again turn the wheel.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Among the earliest examples of this was at Coalbrookdale.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] A horse-powered pump had been installed in 1735 to return water to the pool above the Old Blast Furnace.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This was replaced by a Newcomen engine in 1742–3.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Several new furnaces built in Shropshire in the 1750s were powered in a similar way, including Horsehay and Ketley Furnaces and Madeley Wood or Bedlam Furnaces.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The latter does not seem to have had a pool above the furnace, merely a tank into which the water was pumped.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In other industries, engine-pumping was less common, but Richard Arkwright used an engine to provide additional power for his cotton mill.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Attempts were made to drive machinery by Newcomen engines, but the engines weren't well suited to this work as the delay between power strokes produced a very jerky motion.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] There were attempts to smooth the motion by making Newcomen engines with two cylinders which acted on the crank alternately, the two main firms offering these being Francis Thompson of Ashover, Derbyshire (who patented the idea in 1793), and Batemen and Sherratt of Manchester.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The main problem with the Newcomen design was that it used energy inefficiently, and was therefore expensive to operate.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] After the water vapor within was cooled enough to create the vacuum, the cylinder walls were cold enough to condense some of the steam as it was admitted during the next intake stroke.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This meant that a considerable amount of fuel was being used just to heat the cylinder back to the point where the steam would start to fill it again.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] As the heat losses were related to the surfaces, while useful work related to the volume, increases in the size of the engine increased efficiency, and Newcomen engines became larger in time.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] However, efficiency did not matter very much within the context of a colliery, where coal was freely available.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Newcomen's engine was only replaced when James Watt improved it in 1769 to avoid this problem (Watt had been asked to repair a model of a Newcomen engine by Glasgow University—a small model that exaggerated the problem).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In the Watt steam engine, condensation took place in an exterior condenser unit, attached to the steam cylinder via a pipe.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] When a valve on the pipe was opened, the vacuum in the condenser would, in turn, evacuate that part of the cylinder below the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This eliminated the cooling of the main cylinder walls and such, and dramatically reduced fuel use.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] It also enabled the development of a double-acting cylinder, with both upwards and downwards power strokes, increasing amount of power from the engine without a great increase in the size of the engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Watt's prototype engine in 1769, revealed that he needed a step-change in precision for the cylinders.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In the Newcomen engine the seal could be effected with copious amounts of water, but Watt's cylinder had to operate without the water flood as the idea was to maintain the cylinder at steam temperature.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Watt could not make his engines until 1774, when John Wilkinson devised an accurate cylinder boring method, and was given an exclusive contract for producing the cylinders as a result.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In 1776 Watt wrote to Smeaton that "Mr Wilkinson has improved the art of boring cylinders; so that I promise upon a 72 inch cylinder being not further distant from absolute truth, than the thickness of a slim sixpence in the worst part".
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Boulton and Watt production started the very next year, but the new engines did not eliminate Newcomen engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Watt's vigorous defence of his patents resulted in the continued use of the Newcomen engine in an effort to avoid royalty payments.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Boulton and Watt relied on others to make the engine parts (e.g.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] John Wilkinson) until 1795 and this resulted in delays, plus they favoured a contract with ongoing payments based on the amount of coal saved.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Competitors such as Bateman (from 1791 Bateman and Sherratt) had their own foundry in Salford and built many atmospheric engines, many breaching Watt's patent, leading to a court case in 1796 and a substantial settlement, but Boulton & Watt refused to let them licence the separate condenser.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] However Bateman and Sherratt, and others, continued to sell atmospheric engines, some designed to use the separate condenser when the Watt patent expired.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] When the patents expired in 1800, there was a rush to use the separate condenser and so the remaining Newcomen engines were adapted or replaced, even in collieries.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] However the use of atmospheric engines, albeit with the Watt separate condenser, was to continue for many years as the use of high-pressure steam boilers was in its early stages, and as yet unproven.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The Newcomen Memorial Engine can be seen operating in Newcomen's home town of Dartmouth, where it was moved in 1963 by the Newcomen Society.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This is believed to date from 1725, when it was initially installed at the Griff Colliery near Coventry.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] An engine was installed at a colliery in Ashton-under-Lyne in about 1760.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Known locally as *Fairbottom Bobs* it is now preserved at the Henry Ford Museum in Dearborn, Michigan.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The only Newcomen-style engine still extant in its original location is at what is now the Elsecar Heritage Centre, near Barnsley in South Yorkshire.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] This was probably the last commercially used Newcomen-style engine, as it ran from 1795 until 1923.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The engine underwent extensive conservation works, together with its original shaft and engine-house, which were completed in autumn 2014.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] There are two static examples of a Newcomen Engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] A second example is in the National Museum of Scotland.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Formerly at Caprington Colliery at Kilmarnock.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Another example, originally used at Farme Colliery is on display at Summerlee, Museum of Scottish Industrial Life; unusually it was used for winding rather than water pumping, and had been in operation for almost a century when examined in situ in 1902.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] In 1986, a full-scale operational replica of the 1712 Newcomen Steam Engine was completed at the Black Country Living Museum in Dudley.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] It is the only full-size working replica of the engine in existence and is believed to be a couple of miles away from the site of the first completed engine, erected in 1712.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The 'fire engine' as it was known, is an impressive brick building from which a wooden beam projects through one wall.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] Rods hang from the outer end of the beam and operate pumps at the bottom of the mine shaft which raise the water to the surface.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The engine itself is simple, with only a boiler, a cylinder and piston and operating valves.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] A coal fire heats the water in the boiler which is little more than a covered pan and the steam generated then passes through a valve into the brass cylinder above the boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The cylinder is more than 2 metres long and 52 centimetres in diameter.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/atmospheric-engine] The steam in the cylinder is condensed by injecting cold water and the vacuum beneath the piston pulls the inner end of the beam down and causes the pump to move.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A **high pressure watertube boiler** (also spelled *water-tube* and *water tube*) is a type of boiler in which water circulates in tubes heated externally by fire.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Fuel is burned inside the furnace, creating hot gas which boils water in the steam-generating tubes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In smaller boilers, additional generating tubes are separate in the furnace, while larger utility boilers rely on the water-filled tubes that make up the walls of the furnace to generate steam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The heated water/steam mixture then rises into the steam drum.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Here, saturated steam is drawn off the top of the drum.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In some services, the steam passes through tubes in the hot gas path (a superheater) to become superheated.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Superheated steam is a dry gas and therefore is typically used to drive turbines, since water droplets can severely damage turbine blades.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Saturated water at the bottom of the steam drum returns to the lower drum via large-bore 'downcomer tubes', where it pre-heats the feedwater supply.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] (In large utility boilers, the feedwater is supplied to the steam drum and the downcomers supply water to the bottom of the waterwalls).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] To increase economy of the boiler, exhaust gases are also used to pre-heat combustion air blown into the burners, and to warm the feedwater supply in an economizer.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Such watertube boilers in thermal power stations are also called *steam generating units*.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The older fire-tube boiler design, in which the water surrounds the heat source and gases from combustion pass through tubes within the water space, is typically a much weaker structure and is rarely used for pressures above 2.4 MPa (350 psi).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A significant advantage of the watertube boiler is that there is less chance of a catastrophic failure: there is not a large volume of water in the boiler nor are there large mechanical elements subject to failure.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A water-tube boiler was patented by Blakey of England in 1766 and was made by Dallery of France in 1780.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "The ability of watertube boilers to be designed without the use of excessively large and thick-walled pressure vessels makes these boilers particularly attractive in applications that require dry, high-pressure, high-energy steam, including steam turbine power generation".
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Besides, they are frequently employed in power generation plants where large quantities of steam (ranging up to 500 kg/s) having high pressures i.e. approximately 16 megapascals (160 bar) and high temperatures reaching up to 550 °C are generally required.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] For example, the Ivanpah solar-power station uses two Rentech Type-D watertube boilers for plant warmup, and when operating as a fossil-fueled power station.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Modern boilers for power generation are almost entirely water-tube designs, owing to their ability to operate at higher pressures.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Where process steam is required for heating or as a chemical component, then there is still a small niche for fire-tube boilers.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One notable exception is in typical nuclear-power stations (Pressurized Water Reactors), where the steam generators are generally configured similar to firetube boiler designs.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In these applications the hot gas path through the "Firetubes" actually carries the very hot/high pressure primary coolant from the reactor, and steam is generated on the external surface of the tubes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Their ability to work at higher pressures has led to marine boilers being almost entirely watertube.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This change began around 1900, and traced the adoption of turbines for propulsion rather than reciprocating (i.e. piston) engines – although watertube boilers were also used with reciprocating engines, and firetube boilers were also used in many marine turbine applications.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There has been no significant adoption of water-tube boilers for railway locomotives.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A handful of experimental designs were produced, but none of them were successful or led to their widespread use.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most water-tube railway locomotives, especially in Europe, used the Schmidt system.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most were compounds, and a few uniflows.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Norfolk and Western Railway's *Jawn Henry* was an exception, because it used a steam turbine combined with an electric transmission.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Not successful and re-boilered with a conventional boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A slightly more successful adoption was the use of hybrid water-tube/fire-tube systems.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] As the hottest part of a locomotive boiler is the firebox, it was an effective design to use water-tubes here and a conventional fire-tube boiler as an economiser (i.e. pre-heater) in the usual position.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One famous example of this was the USA Baldwin 4-10-2 No.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Built as a compound with a boiler pressure of 2,400 kilopascals (350 psi) it successfully covered over 160,000 kilometres (100,000 mi) in service.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] After a year however, it became clear that any improvements were overwhelmed by the extra costs, and it was retired as a museum display at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A series of twelve experimental locomotives were constructed at the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad's Mt.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Clare shops under the supervision of George H.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Emerson, but none of them were replicated in any numbers.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The only water-tube locomotive boiler used in any large numbers was the Brotan boiler, invented by Johann Brotan in Austria in 1902 and found sparsely throughout Europe, although Hungary had around 1,000 in service.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Like the Baldwin 60000, it combined a water-tube firebox with a fire-tube barrel.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Brotan's original characteristic was a long steam drum running *above* the main barrel, resembling a Flaman boiler in appearance.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] While traction engines were usually built with locomotive boiler as its frame, other types of steam road vehicles such as lorries and cars used a wide range of different boiler types.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Road transport pioneers Goldsworthy Gurney and Walter Hancock both used water-tube boilers in their steam carriages around 1830.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most undertype wagons used water-tube boilers.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many manufacturers used variants of the vertical cross-tube boiler, including Atkinson, Clayton, Garrett and Sentinel.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Other types include the Clarkson 'thimble tube' and the Foden O-type wagon's pistol-shaped boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Steam fire-engine makers such as Merryweather usually used water-tube boilers for their rapid steam-raising capacity.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many steam cars used water-tube boilers, and the Bolsover Express company even made a water-tube replacement for the Stanley Steamer fire-tube boiler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The 'D-type' is the most common type of small- to medium-sized boilers, similar to the one shown in the schematic diagram.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It is used in both stationary and marine applications.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It consists of a large steam drum vertically connected to a smaller water drum (a.k.a.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "mud drum") via multiple steam-generating tubes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These drums and tubes as well as the oil-fired burner are enclosed by water-walls - additional water-filled tubes spaced close together so as to prevent gas flow between them.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These water wall tubes are connected to both the steam and water drums, so that they act as a combination of preheaters and downcomers as well as decreasing heat loss to the boiler shell.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The M-type boilers were used in many US World War II warships including hundreds of *Fletcher*-class destroyers.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Three sets of tubes form the shape of an M, and create a separately fired superheater that allows better superheat temperature control.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In addition to the mud drum shown on a D-type boiler, an M-type has a water-screen header and a waterwall header at the bottom of the two additional rows of vertical tubes and downcomers.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The *low water content* boiler has a lower and upper header connected by watertubes that are directly impinged upon from the burner.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This is a "furnace-less" boiler that can generate steam and react quickly to changes in load.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Designed by the American firm of Babcock & Wilcox, this type has a single drum, with feedwater drawn from the bottom of the drum into a header that supplies inclined water-tubes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The watertubes supply steam back into the top of the drum.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Furnaces are located below the tubes and drum.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This type of boiler was used by the Royal Navy's *Leander*-class frigates and in United States Navy New Orleans-class cruisers.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Stirling boiler has near-vertical, almost-straight watertubes that zig-zag between a number of steam and water drums.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Usually there are three banks of tubes in a "four drum" layout, but certain applications use variations designed with a different number of drums and banks.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] They are mainly used as stationary boilers, owing to their large size, although the large grate area does also encourage their ability to burn a wide range of fuels.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Originally coal-fired in power stations, they also became widespread in industries that produced combustible waste and required process steam.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Paper pulp mills could burn waste bark, sugar refineries their bagasse waste.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Named after its designers, the then Poplar-based Yarrow Shipbuilders, this type of three-drum boiler has three drums in a delta formation connected by watertubes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The drums are linked by straight watertubes, allowing easy tube-cleaning.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This does, however, mean that the tubes enter the drums at varying angles, a more difficult joint to caulk.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Outside the firebox, a pair of cold-leg pipes between each drum act as downcomers.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Due to its three drums, the Yarrow boiler has a greater water capacity.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Hence, this type is usually used in older marine boiler applications.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Its compact size made it attractive for use in transportable power generation units during World War II.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In order to make it transportable, the boiler and its auxiliary equipment (fuel oil heating, pumping units, fans etc.), turbines, and condensers were mounted on wagons to be transported by rail.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The White-Forster type is similar to the Yarrow, but with tubes that are gradually curved.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This makes their entry into the drums perpendicular, thus simpler to make a reliable seal.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Thornycroft & Company, the Thornycroft type features a single steam drum with two sets of watertubes either side of the furnace.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These tubes, especially the central set, have sharp curves.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Apart from obvious difficulties in cleaning them, this may also give rise to bending forces as the tubes warm up, tending to pull them loose from the tubeplate and creating a leak.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There are two furnaces, venting into a common exhaust, giving the boiler a wide base tapering profile.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In a forced circulation boiler, a pump is added to speed up the flow of water through the tubes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] After about 1910, the **Baker valve gear** was the main competitor to Walschaerts valve gear for steam locomotives in the United States.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Strictly speaking it was not a valve gear but a variable expansion mechanism adapted to the Walschaerts layout replacing the expansion link and sliding die block.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker arrangement used more pivot bearings or *pin joints*, but avoided the die slip inherent to the expansion link, with the aim of lessening wear and the need for service; it could also facilitate longer valve travel.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In the early 1900s there were many efforts to create a new valve gear to replace the by-then-standard Walschaerts valve gear.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In the United States the Young, Southern, Caprotti and Franklin patterns were used on a few classes, but only the Baker pattern won more than limited acceptance.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Baker Company, of Swanton, Ohio; a builder of steam traction engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The idea came from an employee called Gifford but was developed by the Baker company with the first patents being issued in 1903 and with patents issued through at least November, 1912.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker Locomotive Valve Gear was produced by the Pilliod Co. of Swanton, Ohio.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Subsequent versions were produced up to the end of steam service.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] It was particularly popular on the Norfolk and Western Railway, and almost all later N&W engines used it.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Other extensive users included the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Nickel Plate Road, the New York Central Railroad and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] There was always debate about the advantages of Baker gear, the main criticism being the number of pin joints and possible lost motion.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] While popular with railroads on the east, western states tended to continue with the Walschaerts pattern.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In Britain, Baker gear was popular amongst model engineers but in full-size practice the length of the yoke and the width of the assembly may have been difficult to accommodate within the restricted loading gauge.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Other locomotives to use Baker valve gear were the New Zealand Railways J class, Ja class, Jb class, some Ka class, and the South Australian Railways 620 class.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker valve gear replaces the expansion link of the Walschaerts gear with an assembly of levers and links which produces the same effect of allowing continuous variation valve travel.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The remainder of the gear is the same, so that the return crank and combination lever take the same form, although the proportions are usually modified.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Pilliod Co. sold the gear as a single assembly which was mounted on the frame in the location ordinarily occupied by the Walschaerts expansion link.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The parts were arranged so that when the yoke was centered, the connection of the main link to the bellcrank was in a line with the two pivots on the yoke.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] At this point, the back and forth motion of the lower end of the main link left the top relatively motionless as main link swung back and forth on the swing links.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In forward motion, the yoke was pushed forward, so that its upper pivot was in front of the bell crank-main link connection.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Moving the eccentric arm back and forth lowered and raised the top of the main link.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] This motion was translated by the bellcrank into back and forth motion of the radius rod.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The angle of the yoke controlled the relative motion, and therefore the cutoff; tilting the yoke backwards reversed the motion of the radius rod.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] A **bash valve** is a valve within a piston engine, used to control the admission of the working fluid.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] They are directly actuated valves, operated by contact between the piston and the valve tip.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves have the advantage of great simplicity, for manufacture and operation.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Their disadvantages are that their opening and closing times are relatively crudely controlled, compared to other types of valve gear.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The valve is usually constructed as a circular poppet valve with a conical seat, inserted into the cylinder from the outside.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] A protrusion on the inside is hit by the piston as it approaches top dead centre, forcing the valve open.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are usually held closed by the pressure of fluid in the reservoir behind them.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] There may be a light spring to assist closing when the reservoir is empty.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] For this reason they are used as inlet valves, not exhaust.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] An exhaust bash valve would have the cylinder pressure and the piston actuation both acting to open it, with nothing to close it.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are not widely used in steam engines, although they are known.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Most examples were applied to some form of uniflow steam engine; unlike the more common slide and piston-valved engines with their bidirectional-flow ports, uniflow engines use inlet ports at the cylinder ends and an exhaust near the centre.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Although the opening time of a bash valve is fixed, imprecisely controlled and always occurs near top dead centre, this is not a major drawback for a steam engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] A more important requirement is the ability to accurately control the closing time of the valve, and for its duration to be adjustable in order to 'drive' the engine, according to varying load.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Some designs of uniflow engine have used a combined mechanical and electromagnetic valve to do this.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The valve is opened mechanically, then held by an electromagnet.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] This requires less electrical power to merely hold the valve than to open it.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] A patent for such an engine was granted to Sturtevant in 1968.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The same idea has recently been revived as the main feature of an Advanced Uniflow Steam Engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] In this engine, a second valve is used for exhaust purposes in the later part of the cycle too, although this one is bashed shut, rather than opened.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves have also been used for the *ad hoc* conversion of commonplace petrol small engines, such as lawnmowers, into hobbyist steam engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The original petrol engine sparkplug mounting hole is used as the location for a new piston-actuated bash valve, together with the original exhaust valve.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Performance and efficiency are not a need of such projects.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] One successful application for bash valves has been to pneumatic motors.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Owing to the characteristics of compressed air pneumatic power, their simplicity is valuable and their inefficiencies with other fluids are less important.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Compressed air is supplied cold to the motor.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Energy is represented solely by the pressure of the air not, unlike steam, by the combination of pressure and temperature.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Efficient operation of a steam engine relies upon expansion of the steam during the piston stroke, which relies upon accurate valve timing and an early closure of the valve.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] During the expansion phase of the steam it does not expand in a simple isothermal fashion, but does so adiabatically, much of the energy having been supplied as heat rather than pressure.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The compressed air motor is thermodynamically simpler.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] This means that expansion is less important, valve timings are thus longer and less crucial and so a simple valve may be adequate.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] To provide long opening times, the bash valve normally incorporates some form of tappet mechanism.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Rather than a valve that is held open by the piston directly, the valve becomes double-acting and is opened by the piston's impact at one end of the stroke and closed by a further impact at the other end of the stroke.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The tappet and valve are commonly separate, allowing the valve to remain in a well-defined fully open position throughout the stroke, however the tappet is bounced around by the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Where a reciprocating action is produced, such as for a rock drill, the valve may be actuated either by inertia of the frame or by the movement of the working piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] As the piston hammers back and forth, it impacts a small tappet, which in turn moves the air valve and so reverses the flow of air to the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] One form of this, the arc tappet valve, was an important feature of the Ingersoll rock drill, the first successful compressed air rock drill for use in mining and tunneling.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] This used a valve that rotated in a slight arc, rather than sliding.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The valve was double-acting, controlling the air supply for both the power and the return stroke.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The innovation that made this valve so reliable, thus successful, was a separate tappet that was actuated by the piston in passing at the middle of the stroke, rather than being hammered by a jarring direct impact of the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The mid-stroke actuation also opened the valve passageways earlier, before top dead centre, allowing in air that provided a cushioning effect.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] This further improved the action of the drill, giving a powerful stroke on the working piston and drill rod, but with less damaging hammering to the frame of the drill.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are not used in such engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The cylinder peak pressures of an Otto cycle engine are too high for such a valve to remain on its seat.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are also used in a 'single-shot' situation, where a valve is opened once and then remains open until the contents of a pressure vessel are released.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] Such valves are used in some fire extinguishers and pre-charged air rifles.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] These valves are arranged so that once lifted off their seat, pressure underneath the valve becomes sufficient to keep the valve raised and so it remains open until the pressure reservoir is empty.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/bash-valve] The valve is then closed by a light spring.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] A **cataract** was a speed governing device used for single-acting beam engines, particularly (though not exclusively) Cornish engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The earlier atmospheric engines also used cataracts, but these worked on a different principle.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The earlier type of cataract was a form of water clock: a 'tumbling cup' was gradually filled with water.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] When it reached a certain level, the water caused the cup to tip over, which (via a chain link to a lever) opened the injection cock to start the working cycle.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] After each return cycle, the piston would remain at the top of the cylinder until the cup had refilled (the number of strokes per minute could be adjusted by varying the flow of water into the cup).
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] In either case, the cataract is distinctly different from the centrifugal governor, in that it does not control the speed of the engine's stroke, but rather the timing between strokes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The typical installation of a house-built beam engine spanned four floors.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The cylinder and the engine driver's usual working position were located in the 'bottom chamber', approximately at ground level.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Above this were the 'middle chamber', with the cylinder top cover and 'top nozzle' (the upper valve chest), and above that the 'top chamber' or beam chamber.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The earlier type of cataracts, used on atmospheric engines, were located on the middle floor, above the valve gear and connected to it via a chain.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The later type, used with Cornish engines, were positioned at a lower level and connected to the valve gear via rods and underfloor linkages.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The valve gear (or 'working gear') of a Cornish engine is based on the *plug rod*.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] This is a vertical rod, hung from the beam, and moving in parallel to the piston.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Adjustable tappets are attached to this rod.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] These tappets strike long curved iron levers or 'horns' that are carried on three horizontal shafts or 'arbors'.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Each arbor works one of the engine's valves.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] For the Cornish cycles, these valves are the upper steam inlet to the top of the cylinder, the equilibrium valve that links upper and lower portions of the cylinder, and the lower exhaust and condensing water injection valves, which share an arbor.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] By means of a cataract, these engines could be made to run intermittently: making a single stroke, then stopping and waiting for the valves to be released (by the cataract) to begin the next stroke.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The speed of each power stroke was a feature of the engine and was not easily varied, but there was no need for the engines to run continuously, stroke after stroke.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] This was a direct contrast to the rotative beam engine, and the rotary nature of almost all other steam engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Use of a cataract could allow an engine to be operated at only a third of its ungoverned speed.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] When pumping load was variable, cataracts could also be connected and disconnected as required, allowing the engine to work at full speed for a period and then stopped in between.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The cataract itself resembled a small plunger pump.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] It was an iron box in a cistern filled with water, with a plunger or piston set in the top and pressed downwards by a weight.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The water within the pump could only escape through a small tap or valve.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] As the plunger gradually fell, its motion was passed, by a rocking lever and a rod, upwards to the valvegear.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Once the rod had risen sufficiently, this opened the first valve to admit steam into the upper part of the cylinder, beginning a new stroke.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Once the stroke had begun, the cataract's rocking lever was pushed downwards by the engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] This lifted the plunger, which acted as a suction pump within the cataract to refill the plunger box, through a flap valve from its surrounding cistern.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The cistern was kept filled with water by the pump that the engine itself was working.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The water outlet valve was controlled by a rod from the bottom chamber.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] This was used by the engine's driver to control the working speed, according to the work required.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The cataract's actuating rod also had a screw adjuster, which acted to vary the phasing between the inlet and exhaust valves.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] This could be used to give a longer and more effective condensation time, if the condensing water supply was warm, as in the Summer.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] This adjustment appears to have been poorly understood though, and little used by the engine drivers.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The cataract first appeared on Newcomen engines in Cornwall, although their inventor is unknown.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] They were known in Smeaton's time, and they may be another of the developments to Newcomen's engine for which he was responsible.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] James Watt encountered these on his trip to Cornwall in 1777.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] They were of a simpler type, these early cataracts or 'jack in the box' were a simple tumbling box: a wooden box on a pivot was filled with water through an adjustable cock.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] When the box was filled sufficiently to overbalance, the engine's injection valve would be triggered.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] With the original Newcomen cycle, the speed of the return stroke varied according to the boiler pressure, although this still did not affect the strength or speed of the power stroke.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Boulton and Watt used the simple tumbling box design of cataract for some years afterwards, to around 1779.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] After this other designs were used, including a water cataract where the same water was used and recycled continuously and also an air cataract using a circular bellows.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] An air cataract of this type was supplied for the Ale and Cakes Mine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The plunger pump design of cataract had appeared in Cornwall by 1785, but was not Watt's invention.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Unlike the Watt centrifugal governor, the cataract is an open-loop, rather than closed-loop control.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The cataract runs at its own speed, but does not measure the resultant speed of the engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The cataract has also been described as a 'water clock'.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] This assumes that the relationship between the cataract's operation and the engine's speed is fixed, which is a valid assumption for a beam engine as the cataract controls the timing of the engine's stroke, rather than a variable power or throttle valve.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Where a governor controls such a throttle valve, as for the Watt governor, the speed of the engine depends on a complex and unpredictable relation between the engine load, the valve position and the varying efficiency of the engine.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Such governors must use a closed-loop control if they are to maintain an effective and precise regulation.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] One advantage of the independent and open loop nature of the cataract's control was that two engines could be adjusted to run in synchronisation, but in antiphase.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] With pumping engines, this gave a more even output to their pumping.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] With a rotative engine, it was necessary to control the rate at which an engine moved throughout its stroke, not merely to vary the timing between strokes.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] This required the use of a throttle valve in the steam supply.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] As the load on engines uses could vary, closed-loop control such as the engine speed-based centrifugal governor was also needed.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The cataract was thus not used on rotative engines.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Cornish engines were not amenable to control by a throttle valve, as their operating cycle depended on the condensation time more than a throttled steam supply.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Non-rotative beam engines also had no easy means to drive a centrifugal governor.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] For these reasons the cataract remained in service for as long as the Cornish engine did.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] The term 'cataract' became a synonym for dashpot, at least where this was associated with steam engines and their governors.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] They were used as a damping device to avoid over-sensitivity with centrifugal governors.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] Cataracts were also used as an over-speed safety device for direct-acting water pumps.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] A seesaw or 'differential' lever was placed between the pump's piston rod and a cataract adjusted for the pump's normal working speed.
[src:cataract-beam-engine/cataract-beam-engine] If the pump suddenly accelerated, owing to the pump bursting or similar, the piston would overtake the cataract and the action of the differential lever would then close the pump's steam inlet valve and stop the pump, limiting possible damage.
